enTranslation:
The state is broken, but the mountains and rivers remain;
In the city of spring, grass and trees grow thick.
Moved by the times, flowers shed tears;
Grieving separation, birds startle the heart.
Beacon fires have joined three months running;
A letter from home is worth ten thousand gold.
I scratch my white head, ever thinner —
It can scarce hold the hairpin now.

The lingering sun makes the hills and rivers fair;
Spring wind brings the scent of flowers and grass.
The thawed mud flies with swallows;
The warm sand sleeps with mandarin ducks.

Long I heard of the Dongting waters;
Today at last I climb Yueyang Tower.
Wu and Chu split off to the southeast;
Heaven and earth float there day and night.
No word from kin and friends;
Old, sick, I have but this lone boat.
North of the passes, warhorse and war —
Leaning on the rail, I weep.

Empty hills, fresh rain after;
Evening air, autumn arrives.
Bright moon shines through the pines;
Clear spring flows over the stones.
Bamboo rustles — washer-girls return;
Lotus stirs — a fishing boat descends.
Let the spring fragrance fade as it will;
The prince may well stay on.

Idle, I sense the falling of cassia;
Still night, the spring mountain empty.
The moon rises and startles the mountain birds;
Now and then they cry in the spring ravine.

A single carriage, I go to question the frontier;
As an envoy of the vassal state, I pass Juyan.
Like a tumbleweed I leave the Han pass;
Like a north-bound wild goose, enter the Hu sky.
In the vast desert a lone smoke rises straight;
By the long river the setting sun is round.
At Xiao Pass I meet a scout on horse,
Who says the protector is at Yanran.

Spring sleep, unaware of dawn;
Everywhere I hear birds singing.
Last night, the sound of wind and rain;
How many flowers have fallen?

I move my boat and moor at the misty isle;
At dusk, the traveler’s grief is new.
The wilds are vast, the sky lowers on the trees;
The river clear, the moon draws near to me.

In the eighth month the lake is level;
Its waters merge with the clear void.
Mists steam over the Yunmeng marshes;
Waves shake the city of Yueyang.
I would cross, but have no boat or oar;
To sit idle shames this enlightened age.
Watching the anglers,
In vain I harbor a fish-longing heart.

A thousand miles of yellow cloud dims the white sun;
North wind blows the wild geese, snow fills the sky.
Do not mourn that ahead lies no bosom friend;
Under heaven who does not know your name?

Eastward I gaze toward home, the road is long and far;
My two sleeves are wet with tears that will not dry.
Meeting you on horseback, no paper, no brush;
Pray take a word for me—tell them I am well.

North wind rolls the earth and breaks the white grass;
Eighth month in the Tartar sky, and great snow flies.
As if a sudden spring wind came in the night,
Pear blossoms burst on a thousand, ten-thousand trees.
Snow enters the pearl blinds and wets the silken screen;
The fox-fur robe is not warm, the brocade quilt is thin.
The general's horn-bowed bow will not string,
The governor's iron coat is too cold to put on.
The sea of sand is ice, a hundred fathoms deep and crossed;
Gloomy clouds settle, ten thousand li of grey.
In the central tent wine is poured for the guest of return;
The barbarian lute, pipa and Qiang flute are played.
At the camp gate, dusk snow falls without cease;
The wind tugs the frozen red banner, it will not fly.
At the east gate of Luntai I see you depart;
As you go, snow already fills the Tianshan road.
The road winds round the hills and you are lost to sight;
On the snow, only the tracks of your horse remain.

Lush, lush grows the grass upon the ancient plain;
Each year it withers and once more turns green.
Wildfire cannot burn it all away;
When the spring wind blows it springs to life again.
Far fragrance invades the old road;
Sunlit green joins the ruined town.
Once more I see the wanderer off—
The thick grass is full of parting grief.

In the world of men, the fourth month, all flowers spent;
In the mountain temple the peach blossoms just now bloom.
Long I grieved that spring, gone, was nowhere to be found;
I never knew it had turned aside and come here.

Hard it was to meet, and harder still to part;
The east wind has no strength, a hundred flowers fade.
The spring silkworm's thread is spent only at death;
The candle's tears dry only when it turns to ash.
At dawn her mirror grieves that her cloud-hair changes;
At night, chanting, she feels the chill of moonlight.
To Penglai is not a long road from here;
May the blue bird go thither often to seek her.

The brocade zither, unprompted, has fifty strings;
Each string, each bridge, recalls a vanished spring.
Master Zhuang, in his dawn dream, was bewildered into a butterfly;
The King of Wandering Souls bestowed his spring heart on the cuckoo.
Upon the bright sea, under the bright moon, pearls have tears;
On Blue Field, in the warm sun, jade breeds mist.
This feeling—need it wait to become a memory?
Even then, already, it was bewildering.

At Clear and Bright, the rain falls thick and fine;
The traveller upon the road is soul-half-spent.
I ask where a tavern may be found;
A cowherd points afar to Apricot Blossom Village.

Far up the cold mountain, the stone path winds slanting;
Where white clouds are born, there are still men's homes.
I stop my cart, loving the maple grove at dusk;
Frosted leaves are redder than the flowers of the second month.

Mist shrouds the cold water, moonlight shrouds the sand;
At night I moor on the Qinhuai, near the wine-houses.
The singing girls know not the grief of a fallen state;
Across the river they still sing 'The Backyard Flowers.'

Silver candle, autumn light, coldly lights the painted screen;
With a light silk fan she flaps at the drifting fireflies.
The stone steps, night's colour cool as water;
She lies and watches the Herd-boy and Weaving-girl stars.

The moon has set, crows cry, frost fills the sky;
River maples, fisher-fires, and my sorrowful sleep.
Beyond Suzhou, the Cold Mountain Temple;
At midnight its bell reaches the traveller's boat.

Lake-light and autumn moon blend in harmony;
The unruffled surface, like a mirror not yet polished.
Gazing far, the hills and water are a deep green;
In a silver plate, a single green snail.

Alone I love the secluded grass that grows by the ravine;
Above, the oriole sings deep among the trees.
The spring tide, with the rain, grows swift at dusk;
At the deserted ford, a boat lies idle, athwart.

The old man has ridden the yellow crane away;
All that remains is the Yellow Crane Tower.
The yellow crane once gone returns no more;
White clouds for a thousand autumns drift idly on.
The sunny river—Hanyang's trees stand clear and distinct;
Luxuriant grass spreads on Parrot Islet.
At sunset, where is my native land?
On the misty waves of the river, sorrow comes.

The kind mother's hand, the thread;
The wanderer's body, the clothes.
Before he left, she stitched close, close;
Fearing his return be delayed.
Who says the inch-long grass-heart
Can repay the spring sunshine's grace?

I left home young, return old;
My village speech unchanged, my hair silvered.
The village children see me and know me not;
They smile and ask: 'Stranger, whence come you?'

In spring they sow a single grain of millet;
In autumn it yields ten thousand grains.
No field lies idle under heaven;
Yet still the farmers starve and die.

The faintly-seen flying bridge is cut off by the wild mist;
West of the rock-ledge I ask the fishing boat.
Peach blossoms all day drift upon the flowing water;
The cave by the clear stream—on which side does it lie?
